Trending Youtube Videos EDA & Sentiment Analysis

Founded in 2005, YouTube is one of the most popular video sharing websites today, with over 30 millions of visitors per day and 30 hours of videos uploaded every minute.

Everyday, Youtube displays a list of trending videos for all users in each country, from a new song of a popular artist to a new movie trailer, everything in between to help them see what's happening on Youtube and around the world. In this report, I am going to do a comparative analysis on some of the datasets about Youtube trending videos in GB and US to uncover as much insights as possible such as the video preferences of GB and US audiences, audience sentiment as well as the potential factors of what makes a video trending.

Data Overview¶

We will be using three datasets for each country in the analysis. The video dataset contains details of up to 200 listed Youtube trending videos everyday for 40 consecutive days, including video title, channel name, tags, along with statistics such as views, likes, dislike and comments. The comment dataset contains comment texts of these trending videos and the category dataset contains video categories with their unique id.

Data Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasnaek/youtube

Let's import the data file and catch a glimpse on the data.

Cleaning the data¶

After we have done importing and gained some understanding on the data, we need to preprocess or clean the dataset before carrying out any analysis that include

  1. Fixing the shifted row to correct the data types
  2. Handling missing values
  3. Imputing missing values

Fixing the shifted rows

As we've noticed in the GB video dataset, there are incorrect data types in some columns, this is because the data file format has been corrupted during the data scraping process and this has caused shifting of some column values during importing. To fix this, we can create a function that check corrupted rows and amend it by assigning the right values to the columns.

# Function that fix the shifted row
shift_values_videos <- function(df){
  chr <- df[grepl('[A-Za-z]',df$comment_total), ]
  rns <- as.integer(row.names(chr))
  for(row in 1:nrow(df)){
    if(row %in% rns){
      id <- substr(df[row-1,]$date,6,16)
      new_row <- unname(unlist(df[row,]))
      new_row <- append(new_row,id,0)
      new_row <- new_row[1:length(new_row)-1]
      df[row,] <- new_row
      df[row-1,]$date <- substr(df[row-1,]$date,1,5)
    }
  }
  
  return(df)
}

# Apply function on gb video data
gb_videos <- shift_values_videos(gb_videos)

Handling missing values¶

As observed, the comment data file has also been corrupted due to incomplete data and missing comma in the data file. In such case, if we use the usual method to import the data, some of the row values will be jumbled together in the same column (as shown below). To avoid this, we can read in the data lines by lines instead to search for observations that are having missing values. For simplicity, we could just remove these observations from the dataset if they are small.

# Using read_lines methods
fileName <- "GBcomments.csv"
con <- file(fileName,open="r")
gb_comments_lines <- readLines(con)
close(con)

# Remove all lines with less than one backslash
gb_comments_lines <- append(gb_comments_lines[str_count(gb_comments_lines,"\"") > 1],gb_comments_lines[1],0)
gb_comments <- read.table(text = gb_comments_lines, header=T,sep = ",",fill=T,skipNul=T,stringsAsFactors = F,encoding="utf-8")

# Remove all rows that contains characters in the "replies" columns
gb_comments <- gb_comments[!grepl('[A-Za-z]',gb_comments$replies), ]
gb_comments$replies <- as.integer(gb_comments$replies)

# Remove duplicate rows 
gb_comments <- gb_comments %>% 
  group_by(video_id,comment_text) %>%
  summarise(likes = max(likes),replies = max(replies))

Imputing zero values¶

For videos with zero values in their views and likes columns, we impute them by using the median values.

unique_us_videos <- us_videos %>% group_by(video_id) %>% mutate(trending_in_days = n()) %>% top_n(1,date) %>% ungroup() 

# Imputing missing values
unique_gb_videos <- unique_gb_videos %>%  mutate(views=replace(views, views==0,  median(views,na.rm = TRUE)),
                                                 likes=replace(likes, likes==0,  median(likes,na.rm = TRUE)),
                                                 tags=replace(tags, tags=='[none]',  NA))
unique_us_videos <- unique_us_videos %>%  mutate(views=replace(views, views==0,  median(views,na.rm = TRUE)),
                                                 likes=replace(likes, likes==0,  median(likes,na.rm = TRUE)),
                                                 tags=replace(tags, tags=='[none]',  NA))
unique_videos <- rbind(unique_gb_videos,unique_us_videos)

unique_videos <- unique_videos %>%  mutate(views=replace(views, views==0,  median(views,na.rm = TRUE)),
                                           likes=replace(likes, likes==0,  median(likes,na.rm = TRUE)),
                                           tags=replace(tags, tags=='[none]',  NA))

Exploring The Data¶

In this section, we will be doing an EDA that answer on the following questions:

  1. Which Youtube videos/channels/categories have the greatest longetivity and highest popularity on the trending list? How can we use this to explain the video preferences between GB and US audiences?
  2. What are some criteria for videos to be listed on the trending video list?
  3. What are the characteristics of top trending videos?

This project will mainly focus on discovering the important traits of trending and top trending videos and studying how the statistics such as likes, views, comments, trending days correlate with each other using various intuitive graphs and plots. Some of the important metrics including viewer's sentiment and video growth rate will also be accounted in the analysis.

First let's take a quick look at the video statistics.

# function for multi-line title
split_line <- function(sentence,n){
    wc <- wordcount(sentence)
    w <- word(sentence,1,n)
    if(wc <= n){
        return(sentence)
    }else{
        for(i in seq(n+1,wc,n)){
            start <- i
            end <- i+n
            if(wc == start){
                w <- paste(w, word(sentence, start),sep = ' \n ')
                return(w)
            }else if(wc < end){
                w <- paste(w, word(sentence, start, -1),sep = ' \n ')
                return(w)
            }else{
                w <- paste(w, word(sentence, start, end),sep = ' \n ')
            }
            
        }
        return(w)
    }
    
}

Sentiment Towards Videos¶

In Youtube, video viewers are given option to express their subjective opinions towards a video by writing and posting comments. The comments may be critical, suggestive, complimentary or even neutral, every one of it provides important information that help us to determine the audience sentiment or mood towards a particular video. Let's perform a simple sentiment analysis on the video comments using the comment dataset. For simplicity, we combine comments of every unique video and compute an overall sentiment score for the video.

Some preprocessing steps need to be done on the comment data as they are messy and unstructured. We should remove characters and words that are meaningless to our analysis.

# Function to compute sentiment score
get_sentiment_scores <- function(df){
  length  <- dim(df)[1]
  n <- as.integer(length/500)
  counter <- 1
  
  for(i in seq(n)){
    text_vector <- df$text[counter:(counter+499)]
    df$sentiment_score[counter:(counter+499)] <- sentiment(text_vector)$sentiment
    counter <- counter+500
  }

  text_vector <- df$text[counter:length]
  df$sentiment_score[counter:length] <- sentiment(text_vector)$sentiment
  return(df)
}

# Get sentiment scores for GB videos
gb_comments_by_video_id['sentiment_score'] <- 0
gb_comments_by_video_id<- get_sentiment_scores(gb_comments_by_video_id)

# Get sentiment scores for US videos
us_comments_by_video_id['sentiment_score'] <- 0
us_comments_by_video_id<- get_sentiment_scores(us_comments_by_video_id)

We can also categorize the sentiment score based on polarity:

  • scores less than -1 : negative
  • scores in the range of -1 to 1 : neutral
  • scores more than 1 : positive

The scoring system used in this analysis is fairly simple in design but it does give an general assumption of the sentiment. However, we can further improve the precision of the score by introducing a weighting scheme into the system in which the sentiment will be weighted based on the usefulness of a particular comment denoted by its number of replies and likes.

Another factor we can try to look at is the percentage change of the video statistics over time. We can make a rough estimation of the growing speed by calculate the relative growth rate for each video using views, likes, dislikes and comments.

In [137]:
trending_gb_videos <- unique_gb_videos %>% arrange(desc(trending_in_days)) %>% head(10)
trending_us_videos <- unique_us_videos %>% arrange(desc(trending_in_days)) %>% head(10)
gb_videos <- gb_videos  %>%  mutate(VLDC = views+ likes+ dislikes+ comment_total)
  
plot_data_gb <- gb_videos %>% group_by(video_id) %>%
    summarise(r_growth_rate = ((log(last(VLDC, order_by = date)) - log(first(VLDC, order_by = date)))/(n() - 1)) *100) %>%
    mutate(title = mapvalues(video_id,from = unique_gb_videos$video_id, to = unique_gb_videos$title), 
           trending_in_days = mapvalues(video_id,from = unique_gb_videos$video_id, to = unique_gb_videos$trending_in_days))
plot_data_gb$trending_in_days <- as.integer(plot_data_gb$trending_in_days)

unique_gb_videos$r_growth_rate = mapvalues(unique_gb_videos$video_id,from = plot_data_gb$video_id, to = plot_data_gb$r_growth_rate)

us_videos <- us_videos  %>%  mutate(VLDC = views+ likes+ dislikes+ comment_total)

plot_data_us <- us_videos %>% group_by(video_id) %>%
  summarise(r_growth_rate = ((log(last(VLDC, order_by = date)) - log(first(VLDC, order_by = date)))/(n() - 1)) *100) %>%
  mutate(title = mapvalues(video_id,from = unique_us_videos$video_id, to = unique_us_videos$title), 
         trending_in_days = mapvalues(video_id,from = unique_us_videos$video_id, to = unique_us_videos$trending_in_days))
plot_data_us$trending_in_days <- as.integer(plot_data_us$trending_in_days)

unique_us_videos$r_growth_rate = mapvalues(unique_us_videos$video_id,from = plot_data_us$video_id, to = plot_data_us$r_growth_rate)

Features Correlation¶

Here we plot a correlation heatmap to depict the relationship between features.

In [426]:
corrdata <- unique_gb_videos %>% select(c(views, likes, dislikes, comment_total,sentiment_score,r_growth_rate,trending_in_days))

corrdata$sentiment_score <- as.numeric(corrdata$sentiment_score)
corrdata$r_growth_rate <- as.numeric(corrdata$r_growth_rate)

cormat <- cor(corrdata, use = "complete.obs")

get_upper_tri <- function(cormat){
    cormat[lower.tri(cormat)]<- NA
    return(cormat)
  }

upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)

plot_data_gb <- melt(upper_tri, na.rm = TRUE)

p1 <- ggplot(data = plot_data_gb, aes(Var2, Var1, fill = value))+
  geom_tile(color = "white")+
  xlab(' ') +
  ylab('Variables') +
  labs(title = "Correlation Heatmap",subtitle = "GB") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", high = "red", mid = "white", 
                       midpoint = 0, limit = c(-1,1), space = "Lab", 
                       name="Pearson\nCorrelation") +
  theme_minimal()+ 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, 
                                   size = 12, hjust = 1))+
  coord_fixed() 

corrdata <- unique_us_videos %>% select(c(views, likes, dislikes, comment_total,sentiment_score,r_growth_rate,trending_in_days))

corrdata$sentiment_score <- as.numeric(corrdata$sentiment_score)
corrdata$r_growth_rate <- as.numeric(corrdata$r_growth_rate)

cormat <- cor(corrdata, use = "complete.obs")

upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)

plot_data_us <- melt(upper_tri, na.rm = TRUE)

p2 <- ggplot(data = plot_data_us, aes(Var2, Var1, fill = value))+
  geom_tile(color = "white")+
  xlab('Variables') +
  ylab('Variables') +
  labs(subtitle = "US") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", high = "red", mid = "white", 
                       midpoint = 0, limit = c(-1,1), space = "Lab", 
                       name="Pearson\nCorrelation") +
  theme_minimal()+ 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, 
                                   size = 12, hjust = 1))+
  coord_fixed()

grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow = 2)

Summary:

  • Trending videos generally have considerable amount of views, likes and comments.
  • Amount of views, likes and comments have strong positive correlations.
  • The higher the amount of dislike, the lower the sentiment score.
  • Videos in category music and entertainment has higher chance to be listed on trending video list.
  • Videos related to major events such as launching of a new iphone, a new album release, election and festival are more likely to stay in trend for longer period of time.
